04348nam a22005535i 9780231558013DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2022051409  a97802315580137 a10.7312/cali209582doi  a(DE-B1597)664246  a(OCoLC)1371957175  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHG1710.3 7aBUS1140002bisacsh1 aCaliskan, Koray, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aData Money :bInside Cryptocurrencies, Their Communities, Markets, and Blockchains /cKoray Caliskan. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b14 b&w figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Tables and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 The Historical Novelty of Data Money and Its Makers, Markets, and Regulation -- t2 The Materiality of Data Money and the Infrastructure and Taxonomy of Blockchains -- t3 Understanding Cryptocurrency Exchange Platforms and Markets -- t4 Global Cryptocurrency Communities as Data Money Makers -- t5 The Emergence and Demise of a Cryptocurrency Community -- t6 A New Framework for Cryptocurrency Taxation and Exchange Platform Regulation -- t7 What Is to Be Done with Crypto Economies? -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe cryptocurrency world has transformed in a few short years from a niche subculture to a parallel economic universe, reaching a market capitalization of more than $2.5 trillion in 2021 before plummeting in 2022. For their advocates, cryptocurrencies represent a revolution of world-historical significance. To critics, crypto is more of a speculative tool than a true currency. How do tens of thousands of financial actors make these new monies? What forces give cryptocurrencies their value—or take it away? And what does crypto’s spectacular ascent reveal about the nature of money? In this groundbreaking ethnographic analysis of crypto economies and their global markets and communities, Koray Caliskan offers an inside view of how cryptocurrencies are made and traded. He argues that cryptocurrency should be understood as “data money,” a historically novel money type, created as the right to send data privately over an accounting infrastructure called blockchain. Drawing on two years of fieldwork among global cryptocurrency communities and in crypto markets, Caliskan makes visible the production principles of cryptocurrencies and explores how crypto exchanges work from within. He explains why and how we have been misunderstanding, underregulating, and improperly taxing crypto exchanges and actors. He also proposes a radically new way to make sense of new finance and its actors. An invaluable book for all readers seeking to understand cryptocurrency, Data Money sheds new light on a profound transformation of finance and its possible future trajectories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBlockchains (Databases) 0aBlockchains (Databases). 0aCryptocurrencies. 0aCurrency question. 0aDigital currency. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Bitcoin & Cryptocurrencies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074967040uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/cali2095840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231558013423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231558013/original  a978-3-11-074967-0  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles